1 TITL England & Wales, Birth Index, 1837-2005
1 PUBL MyHeritage
1 TEXT Civil registration ŌĆö the government recording of births, marriages, and deaths ŌĆö began in England and Wales on 1 July 1837. Local registration districts had jurisdiction for recording civil events
2 CONC , but were required to send copies of their records each quarter to the General Register Office (GRO) in London. The GRO created indexes to these records which are organized by event, year, and quarte
2 CONC r, and thereunder alphabetically by surname.Information included in the index changed over the years. From inception up to June 1911, the birth index lists: name of child, registration district, and r
2 CONC eference information (volume and page numbers). Since September 1911 the index also includes the motherŌĆÖs maiden surname.Information provided in the index can be used to order a copy of the personŌĆ
2 CONC Ös birth certificate for a fee from the GRO through their Certificate Ordering Service. Depending on the year, full birth certificates may provide: name of child, birth date, birthplace, sex, fatherŌĆ
2 CONC Ös name and occupation, motherŌĆÖs maiden name, informantŌĆÖs name, residence, and relationship to the child, and date of registration.Note: For years where images of the index are available, be sure 
2 CONC to consult the image to verify the information presented to you. Sometimes errors happen during the transcription process. For example, a "5" may have inadvertently been transcribed as a "3". Since th
2 CONC ere is a fee for ordering certificate copies from the GRO, it is especially important to make sure all reference numbers are correct before placing an order.Search tip: Compliance with registration la
2 CONC ws have always been very good. It is estimated that initially about 90-95% of births were reported, but that by 1875 registration was 99%. Since nearly all births were reported, if you are having trou
2 CONC ble finding someone in the index, try searching using various given names or initials. In later years, searching on the combination of childŌĆÖs surname and motherŌĆÖs maiden name (if known), may also
2 CONC  help locate difficult-to-find individuals. If an individual can still not be found, especially in earlier years, try searching local parish records for the childŌĆÖs baptismal record.
