1 TITL Australia Obituary Index from OldNews.com
1 PUBL MyHeritage
1 TEXT In Australia, obituaries in newspapers have played a significant role in commemorating lives and documenting social history. During the early colonial period in the 19th century, obituaries in Austral
2 CONC ian newspapers were often brief and factual, primarily noting names, dates, and basic biographical details. As the nation developed, particularly after the gold rushes and into the 20th century, obitu
2 CONC aries began to offer more detailed accounts of the deceased's life stories, achievements, and contributions to their communities. By the mid-1900s, obituaries had become more personalized, reflecting 
2 CONC the evolving societal values that emphasized individual accomplishments and personal histories. This period also saw a more structured approach, influenced by both funeral homes and newspaper editoria
2 CONC l practices, leading to standardized formats that included sections for death announcements, biographical summaries, lists of survivors, and funeral arrangements. In contemporary Australia, obituaries
2 CONC  continue to serve as important historical records and sources of information for genealogists and historians, preserving the legacies of individuals for future generations.
2 CONC The records in this collection were extracted using machine learning technology and may contain mistakes due to Optical Character Recognition (OCR) technology and the automatic extraction. Users are e
2 CONC ncouraged to fix such mistakes using the ŌĆ£Suggest an alternativeŌĆØ feature that is found on every record page.
2 CONC Images for these newspapers can be viewed on <a id="" href="https://www.oldnews.com/en" class="green" target="_blank" rel="noopener">OldNews.com</a>.
